crowdsourced_yara_results.description: This signature detects an Adobe Type 1 Font. The Type 1 Font Format is a standardized font format for digital imaging applications.
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: InQuest Labs

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis:
While a technical analysis of the PDF's internal structure found no executable content, JavaScript, or automatic actions, the document's visual layer contains a clear phishing attempt. The file presents itself as a security alert from "Allfunds" regarding a mandatory "2FA Security Update," creating a false sense of urgency with a 48-hour deadline.

The document instructs the user to scan a QR code to perform the update. Analysis of this visual content reveals numerous red flags, including grammatical errors ("Your are required"), the use of generic imagery instead of official company logos, and an unusual update method. The QR code decodes to the URL `https://jithiadaproperties.co.ke/.well-known/wildindex.php?&cfg=matthias.saladin@allfunds.com`.

This URL directs the user to an unrelated third-party domain, which is a definitive indicator of a phishing attack. The document is a social engineering lure designed to trick the recipient into visiting a malicious website, likely to harvest credentials or distribute malware. Despite the technically benign structure of the PDF container, the file's overall purpose and content are malicious.
